;; **
;;; ##### Dangling condition
;;; 
;;; Another application condition that plays an important role in graph transformation systems is the so-called _dangling condition_. It restricts deletion of graph nodes in an "unknown" context. A graph transformation system that enforces the dangling condition does not allow deletion of any nodes unless all their connections (in an outgoing edges) are also identified in the graph transformation rule. 
;;; 
;;; As an example, consider graph `g` below and the following rule `delworld`, which matches a `World` node and deletes it.
;; **

;; @@
(def g (-> (newgrape) hello world))
(view g)
