;; **
;;; Clearly, rule `delworld` would find a match in graph `g`. However, deleting the matched `World` node would leave a "dangling" `to` edge. Of course, such "dangling" edges are not allowed, since the result would no longer be a valid graph. Two alternatives remain:
;;; 1. either we could also automatically delete any dangling edges, or
;;; 1. we forbid any deletes that would leave dangling edges.
;;; 
;;; The second option is called the _dangling (application) condition_.
;;; 
;;; By default, _GrapeVine_ rules do not enforce the _dangling condition_. In other words, deletes in unkown contexts are allowed and any dangling edges are automatically deleted as well. (as demonstrated below)
;; **

;; @@
(-> g delworld view)
;; @@
