;; <=

;; **
;;; Of course, internally, each node has a unique ID in the graph database, but this key is not considered here. Therefore, the two graphs above are said to be **identical (_up to isomorphism_)**.
;;; 
;;; This notion of graph equivalence is in line with the mathematical foundation of graph transformations (based on category theory), which defines the graph produced in a transformation only up to isomorphism. In this theory, the above operation would produce only a _single_ graph.
;;; 
;;; The default behaviour of rule applications in _GrapeVine_ therefore represents an approximation of that mathematical semantics. This is akin to the behaviour of other tools that implement mathematical functions. For example, concrete relational databases may return query results with duplicate rows, while the mathematical foundation (based on set theory) does not consider such duplicates. Concrete query languages (like SQL) offer operations to filter query results for duplicates. 
;;; 
;;; 
;;; The reason by relational databases do not filter out duplicate results by default is to avoid performance penalties. Checking graphs for duplicates up to isomorphism is even more expensive. _GrapeVine_ therefore does not filter structurally equivalent results by default.
;;; 
;;; ## Filtered rule applications
;;; 
;;; In addition to the default rule applications (which may produce duplicate results), _GrapeVine_ provides filtered rule applications__. 
;;; 
;;; A filtered rule application returns graphs that are guaranteed to exclude duplicates.
;;; 
;;; Invoking an filtered rule is simply done by adding an hash sign (`#`) after the rule name, to indicate that non-equal results are desired:
;; **

;; @@
(view (rel2# g))
